# This is a regression test for a bug in the capped multiplier model: 
# computeCPUCapacityWithCap subtracts background CPU when
# deriving per-store capacity, which mistakenly broke the naive
# model's invariant:
#
#   sum(store loads) / sum(store capacities) = NodeCPURateUsage / NodeCPURateCapacity
#
# Setup: single node n1 with two stores.
# - s1: store CPU load=200, capacity computed by capped model
# - s2: store CPU load=300, capacity computed by capped model
# - Physical node CPU: load=800, capacity=2000.
#   The gap (800 - 500 = 300) is background CPU that the capped model
#   excluded from store capacities.
#
# With the capped model, n1's store values no longer recover the
# physical node utilization:
#
#   sum(store loads) / sum(store capacities) = 500/2000 = 25%
#   NodeCPURateUsage / NodeCPURateCapacity   = 800/2000 = 40%  (real)
#
# MakeStoreLoadMsg addresses this by passing physical node CPU values
# directly through StoreLoadMsg.NodeCPULoad/NodeCPUCapacity.
#
# Without the fix, NodeCPULoad would be derived from store sums:
#
#   nodes-cpu-load = 500  (sum of 200+300, but real node CPU = 800)
#   node utilization = 25%  (but real = 40%)
#
# With the fix:
#
#   nodes-cpu-load = 800  (physical NodeCPURateUsage)
#   node utilization = 40%  (correct)

# Register two stores on node 1.
set-store store-id=1 node-id=1
----

set-store store-id=2 node-id=1
----

# Store-level CPU loads: s1=200, s2=300 (sum=500).
# Physical node CPU: load=800, capacity=2000. The 300 gap (800-500) is
# background CPU that the capped model excluded from store capacities.
#
# node-cpu-load=800 (physical) differs from what summing store loads
# would give (500).
make-store-load-msg store-id=1 node-id=1 num-stores=2 cpu-per-second=200 stores-cpu-rate=500 node-cpu-usage=800 node-cpu-capacity=2000
----
store-id=1 node-id=1 load=[200,0,0] capacity=[625,9223372036854775807,0] secondary-load=0 load-time=0s node-cpu-load=800 node-cpu-capacity=2000

make-store-load-msg store-id=2 node-id=1 num-stores=2 cpu-per-second=300 stores-cpu-rate=500 node-cpu-usage=800 node-cpu-capacity=2000
----
store-id=2 node-id=1 load=[300,0,0] capacity=[625,9223372036854775807,0] secondary-load=0 load-time=0s node-cpu-load=800 node-cpu-capacity=2000

# nodes-cpu-load=800 (physical node value from MakeStoreLoadMsg),
# not 500 (what store-level summing would give). Node utilization
# is 40% (800/2000), not 25% (500/2000).
load-summary
